It turns out that the `lazy` attribute is initialised in this block of Hibernate code:

    lazy = persistentClass.isLazy() &amp;&amp; (
    		// TODO: this disables laziness even in non-pojo entity modes:
    		!persistentClass.hasPojoRepresentation() ||
    		!ReflectHelper.isFinalClass( persistentClass.getProxyInterface() )
    );

The difference results from the `isFinalClass()` check - classes are final by default in Kotlin, but not in Java. Making the entity classes `open` fixed the problem.

